**Hispanic and Latino Americans** are [Americans](/Americans) who have a [Hispanic](/Hispanic) or [Latin American](/Latin_American) background, culture, or family origin. [3][4][5][6] This demographic group includes all Americans who identify as [Hispanic](/Hispanic) or [Latino](/Latino_(demonym)), regardless of [race](/Race_and_ethnicity_in_the_United_States_census). [7][8][9][10][11][12] As of July 1, 2024, the Hispanic and Latino population was estimated at 68,086,153, representing approximately 20% of the total [U.S. population](/Demographics_of_the_United_States), making them the [second-largest group](/Race_and_ethnicity_in_the_United_States) in the country after the [non-Hispanic White](/Non-Hispanic_whites) population. [13]

"Origin" can be viewed as the ancestry, nationality group, lineage, or country of birth of the person, parents, or ancestors before their arrival into the United States of America. People who identify as Hispanic or Latino may be of any race, because, similarly to what occurred during the colonization and post-independence of the United States, Latin American countries have had populations made up of multiracial and monoracial descendants of settlers from the [metropole](/Metropole) of a European [colonial empire](/Colonial_empire) (in the case of Latin American countries, [Spanish and Portuguese settlers](/Iberian_Peninsula)), unlike the [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) that would form the United States, which received settlers from the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)). In addition, there are also monoracial and multiracial descendants of [Indigenous peoples of the Americas](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) (Native Americans), [descendants of African slaves](/African_diaspora) brought to Latin America in the colonial era, and post-independence immigrants from [Europe](/Europe), the [Middle East](/Middle_East), and [East Asia](/East_Asia). [14][15][16][17]

As one of only two specifically designated categories of [ethnicity in the United States](/Race_and_ethnicity_in_the_United_States_census), Hispanics and Latinos form a [pan-ethnicity](/Pan-ethnicity) incorporating a diversity of inter-related cultural and linguistic heritages, in which the use of the [Spanish](/Spanish_language) language is the most important common element. The largest national origin groups of Hispanic and Latino Americans, in order of population size, are: [Mexican](/Mexicans), [Puerto Rican](/Puerto_Ricans), [Cuban](/Cubans), [Salvadoran](/Salvadorans), [Dominican](/People_of_the_Dominican_Republic), [Colombian](/Colombians), [Guatemalan](/Guatemalans), [Honduran](/Hondurans), [Ecuadorian](/Ecuadorians), [Peruvian](/Peruvians), [Venezuelan](/Venezuelans), and [Nicaraguan](/Nicaraguans). Although commonly embraced by Latino communities, Brazilians are officially not considered Hispanic or Latino. [18][19] The predominant origin of regional Hispanic and Latino populations varies widely in different locations across the country. [15][20][21][22][23] In 2012, Hispanic Americans were the second fastest-growing ethnic group by percentage growth in the United States after [Asian Americans](/Asian_Americans). [24]

Hispanic Americans of [Indigenous American](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) descent and European (typically Spanish) descent are the second oldest racial group (after the [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States)) to inhabit much of what is today the United States. [25][26][27][28] Spain colonized large areas of what is today the [American Southwest](/Southwestern_United_States) and [West Coast](/West_Coast_of_the_United_States), as well as Florida. Its holdings included all of present-day California, Nevada, Utah, Arizona, New Mexico, Texas, and Florida, as well as parts of Wyoming, Colorado, Kansas, and Oklahoma, all of which constituted part of the [Viceroyalty of New Spain](/Viceroyalty_of_New_Spain), based in [Mexico City](/Mexico_City). Later, this vast territory (except Florida, which Spain ceded to the United States in 1821) became part of Mexico after its independence from Spain in 1821 and until the end of the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War) in 1848.

## Terminology

•
Further information: [Hispanic and Latino (ethnic categories)](/Hispanic_and_Latino_(ethnic_categories))

The [Spanish Harlem Orchestra](/Spanish_Harlem_Orchestra) in [Manhattan](/Manhattan). New York City is home to nearly 3 million Latino Americans, the largest [Hispanic](/Hispanic) population of any city outside [Latin America](/Latin_America) and [Spain](/Spain).

The terms [Hispanic](/Hispanic) and [Latino](/Latino_(demonym)) refer to an [ethnicity](/Ethnicity). "Hispanic" first came into popular use to refer to individuals with origins in Spanish-speaking countries after the Office of Management and Budget created the classification in 1977, as proposed by a subcommittee composed of three government employees—a Cuban, a Mexican, and a Puerto Rican American. [29] The [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau) defines being Hispanic as being a member of an ethnicity, rather than being a member of a particular [race](/Race_(human_categorization)), and thus, people who are members of this group may also be members of any race. [15][30][31] In a 2015 national survey of self-identified Hispanics, 56% said that being Hispanic is part of both their racial and ethnic background, while smaller numbers considered it part of their ethnic background only (19%) or racial background only (11%). [30] Hispanics may be of any linguistic background; in a 2015 survey, 71% of American Hispanics agreed that it "is not necessary for a person to speak Spanish to be considered Hispanic/Latino." [32] Hispanic and Latino people may share some commonalities in their language, culture, history, and heritage.

The [National Hispanic Cultural Center](/National_Hispanic_Cultural_Center) in [Albuquerque, New Mexico](/Albuquerque,_New_Mexico); Hispanics make up half of New Mexico's population. [33]

The [Smithsonian Institution](/Smithsonian_Institution) defends that the term "Latino" should also include peoples with Portuguese roots, such as [Brazilians](/Brazilians), and not only those of Spanish-language origin. [34][35] The difference between the terms "Hispanic" and "Latino" is ambiguous to some people. [36] The U.S. Census Bureau equates the two terms and defines them as referring exclusively to Hispanic people [37][38] and those from Spain or the Spanish-speaking countries of the Americas. After the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War) concluded in 1848, the term "Hispanic" or "Spanish American" was primarily used to describe the [Hispanos of New Mexico](/Hispanos_of_New_Mexico) within the [American Southwest](/Southwestern_United_States). The [1970 United States census](/1970_United_States_census) controversially broadened the definition to "a person of Mexican, Puerto Rican, Cuban, Dominican, South or Central American, or other Spanish culture or origin, regardless of race." This is now the common formal and colloquial definition of the term within the United States, outside of New Mexico. [39][40] This definition is consistent with the 21st-century usage by the U.S. Census Bureau and [OMB](/Office_of_Management_and_Budget), as the two agencies use both terms "Hispanic" and "Latino" interchangeably. The [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) mentions that some researchers defend that the term "Hispanic" is strictly limited to [Spain](/Spain), [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico), and all countries where [Spanish](/Spanish_language) is the only official language, whereas "Latino" could include all countries in [Latin America](/Latin_America) (even [Brazil](/Brazil), regardless of the fact that Portuguese is its only official language), but not Spain and Portugal. [3]

[Mariachi Plaza](/Mariachi_Plaza) in [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles); Hispanics form the largest ethnic group in [California](/California), at 15.7 million people, or 40.4% of the total population.

The terms Latino and Latina are words from [Italy](/Italy) and are ultimately from [ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome). In English, the term "Latino" is a condensed form of "latinoamericano," the Spanish term for a Latin American, or someone who comes from Latin America. The term "Latino" has developed a number of definitions. This definition, as a "male Latin American inhabitant of the United States," [41] is the oldest definition used in the United States; it was first used in 1946. [41] Under this definition, a [Mexican American](/Mexican_Americans) or [Puerto Rican](/Puerto_Ricans), for example, is both a Hispanic and a Latino. [42][43][44][45][46][47] In the United States, both [Brazilian Americans](/Brazilian_Americans) and [Italian Americans](/Italian_Americans) are officially not considered "Latino," [48] as they are for the most part descended from immigrants from non-Hispanic countries, unless they happen to have had recent history in a Latin American country.

Preference of use between the terms among Hispanics in the United States often depends on where users of the respective terms reside. Those in the Eastern United States tend to prefer the term "Hispanic," whereas those in the West tend to prefer "Latino." [14]

The US ethnic designation "Latino" is abstracted from the longer form *latinoamericano*. [49] The element *Latino-* is actually an indeclinable, compositional form in *-o* (i.e., an *elemento compositivo*) that is employed to coin compounded formations (similar to *franc*- in *francocanadiense* 'French-Canadian,' or *ibero*- in *iberorrománico*, [50] etc.).

The [Latino Cultural Center](/Latino_Cultural_Center) in [Dallas](/Dallas); Hispanics are the largest ethnic group in [Texas](/Texas), making up 11.4 million people, or 39.3% of the population.

The term [Latinx](/Latinx) (and similar [neologism](/Neologism) [Xicanx](/Xicanx)) have gained some usage. [51][52] The adoption of the "X" would be "[r]eflecting new consciousness inspired by more recent work by LGBTQI and feminist movements, some Spanish-speaking activists are increasingly using a yet more inclusive 'x' to replace the 'a' and 'o,' in a complete break with the [gender binary](/Non-binary_gender)." Among the advocates of the term "LatinX," one of the most frequently cited complaints of gender bias in the Spanish language is that a group of mixed or unknown gender would be referred to as *Latinos*, whereas *Latinas* refers to a group of women only (but this is changed immediately to *Latinos* if even a single man joins this female group). [53] A 2020 Pew Research Center survey found that about 3% of Hispanics use the term (mostly women), and only around 23% have even heard of the term. Of those, 65% said it should not be used to describe their ethnic group. [55] Another gender-neutral term, like "Latinx," is "Latine." Though "Latinx" is quite challenging to say in Spanish, "Latine" is easy. Spanish speakers are increasingly adopting this term, which originated in Spanish-speaking countries. [56]

Some have pointed out that the term "Hispanic" refers to a pan-ethnic identity, one that spans a range of races, national origins, and linguistic backgrounds. "Terms like Hispanic and Latino do not fully capture how we see ourselves," says Geraldo Cadava, an associate professor of history and Hispanic studies at [Northwestern University](/Northwestern_University). [57]

According to a 2020 [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey) data, more than two-thirds of Brazilians in the U.S. described themselves as Hispanic or Latino. [11] In 2017, a small minority of [Portuguese Americans](/Portuguese_Americans) (2%) and [Filipino Americans](/Filipino_Americans) (1%) self-identified as Hispanic. [citation needed]

