### 16th and 17th centuries

Founded by the [Spanish](/Spanish_Empire) in 1565, [St. Augustine, Florida](/St._Augustine,_Florida) is the [oldest continuously inhabited](/List_of_North_American_settlements_by_year_of_foundation) European-established settlement in the [contiguous United States](/Contiguous_United_States).

Explorers were pioneers in the territory of the present-day United States. The first confirmed European landing in the continental United States was by [Juan Ponce de León](/Juan_Ponce_de_Le%C3%B3n), who landed in 1513 at a lush shore he christened [La Florida](/Florida). In the next three decades, the small numbers of Spanish individuals became the first Europeans to reach the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains), the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River), the [Grand Canyon](/Grand_Canyon), and the [Great Plains](/Great_Plains). Ships sailed along the [Atlantic Coast](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States), penetrating to present-day [Bangor, Maine](/Bangor,_Maine), and up the [Pacific Coast](/West_Coast_of_the_United_States) as far as [Oregon](/Oregon). From 1528 to 1536, [Álvar Núñez Cabeza de Vaca](/%C3%81lvar_N%C3%BA%C3%B1ez_Cabeza_de_Vaca) and three fellows (including an African named [Estevanico](/Estevanico)), from a Spanish expedition that foundered, journeyed from Florida to the [Gulf of California](/Gulf_of_California). In 1540, [Hernando de Soto](/Hernando_de_Soto) undertook an extensive exploration of the present United States.

Also in 1540, [Francisco Vásquez de Coronado](/Francisco_V%C3%A1squez_de_Coronado) led 2,000 mostly Mexican natives across today's [Arizona](/Arizona)–Mexico border and traveled as far as central [Kansas](/Kansas), close to the exact geographic center of what is now the continental United States. Other Spanish explorers of US territory include, among others: [Alonso Alvarez de Pineda](/Alonso_Alvarez_de_Pineda), [Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón](/Lucas_V%C3%A1zquez_de_Ayll%C3%B3n), [Pánfilo de Narváez](/P%C3%A1nfilo_de_Narv%C3%A1ez), [Sebastián Vizcaíno](/Sebasti%C3%A1n_Vizca%C3%ADno), [Gaspar de Portolà](/Gaspar_de_Portol%C3%A0), [Pedro Menéndez de Avilés](/Pedro_Men%C3%A9ndez_de_Avil%C3%A9s), [Álvar Núñez Cabeza de Vaca](/%C3%81lvar_N%C3%BA%C3%B1ez_Cabeza_de_Vaca), [Tristán de Luna y Arellano](/Trist%C3%A1n_de_Luna_y_Arellano), and [Juan de Oñate](/Juan_de_O%C3%B1ate), and non-Spanish explorers working for the Spanish Crown, such as [Juan Rodríguez Cabrillo](/Juan_Rodr%C3%ADguez_Cabrillo).

[San Miguel Chapel](/San_Miguel_Mission), built in 1610 in [Santa Fe, New Mexico](/Santa_Fe,_New_Mexico), is the oldest church structure in the United States.

In 1565, the Spanish created the first permanent European settlement in the continental United States, at [St. Augustine, Florida](/St._Augustine,_Florida). Spanish missionaries and colonists founded settlements, including in present-day [Santa Fe, New Mexico](/Santa_Fe,_New_Mexico), [El Paso](/El_Paso,_Texas), [San Antonio](/San_Antonio), [Tucson](/Tucson,_Arizona), [Albuquerque](/Albuquerque,_New_Mexico), [San Diego](/San_Diego), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), and [San Francisco](/San_Francisco). [58]

Settlements in the [American Continent](/American_Continent) were part of a broader network of trade routes that connected Europe, Africa, and the Americas. The mostly Tlaxcalan settlers established trade connections with other indigenous peoples, exchanging goods such as [furs](/Fur), [hides](/Hide_(skin)), [agricultural](/Agricultural) products, and manufactured goods. [citation needed] These trade networks contributed to the economic development of colonies and facilitated cultural exchange between different groups. [citation needed]

### 18th and 19th centuries

•
See also: [Battle of the Alamo](/Battle_of_the_Alamo), [Mexican Cession](/Mexican_Cession), [Gadsden Purchase](/Gadsden_Purchase), and [Treaty of Paris (1898)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1898))

[Mission San Carlos Borromeo de Carmelo](/Mission_San_Carlos_Borromeo_de_Carmelo), established in 1770, was the headquarters of the [Californian mission system](/Spanish_missions_in_California) from 1797 until 1833.

As late as 1783, at the end of the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) (a conflict in which Spain [aided and fought](/Spain_in_the_American_Revolutionary_War) alongside the rebels), Spain held claim to roughly half the territory of today's continental United States. From 1819 to 1848, the United States increased its area by roughly a third at Spanish and Mexican expense, acquiring the present-day [U.S states](/U.S._state) of [California](/California), [Texas](/Texas), [Nevada](/Nevada), [Utah](/Utah), most of [Colorado](/Colorado), [New Mexico](/New_Mexico), and [Arizona](/Arizona), and parts of [Oklahoma](/Oklahoma), [Kansas](/Kansas), and [Wyoming](/Wyoming) through the [Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo](/Treaty_of_Guadalupe_Hidalgo) after the [Mexican-American War](/Mexican-American_War), [59] as well as [Florida](/Florida) through the [Adams-Onís treaty](/Adams-On%C3%ADs_treaty), [60] and the [U.S territory](/Territories_of_the_United_States) of [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico) through the [Spanish-American War](/Spanish%E2%80%93American_War) in 1898. [61] Many Latinos residing in those regions during that period gained U.S. citizenship. Nonetheless, many long-established Latino residents faced significant difficulties post-citizenship. With the arrival of [Anglo-Americans](/Anglo) in these newly incorporated areas, Latino inhabitants struggled to maintain their land holdings, political influence, and cultural traditions. [62][63]

The 1836 [Battle of the Alamo](/Battle_of_the_Alamo), part of the [Texas Revolution](/Texas_Revolution), was fought between forces of [Mexico](/Centralist_Republic_of_Mexico) and the [Republic of Texas](/Republic_of_Texas).

The discovery of gold in California in 1848 attracted people from diverse backgrounds, including Hispanic and Latino miners, merchants, and settlers. The Gold Rush led to a population boom and rapid economic growth in California, transforming the social and political landscape of the region.

Many Hispanic natives lived in the areas that the United States acquired, and a new wave of Mexican, Central American, Caribbean, and South American immigrants moved to the United States for new opportunities. This was the beginning of a demographic that would rise dramatically over the years. [64]

### 20th and 21st centuries

Between 1928 and 1939, between [300,000 and 2 million Mexicans and Mexican-Americans were deported from the United States](/Mexican_Repatriation), 40–60% of whom were American citizens. In 1954, [Operation Wetback](/Operation_Wetback) deported another 250,000.

During the 20th and 21st centuries, Hispanic immigration to the United States increased markedly following changes to the [immigration law](/Immigration_to_the_United_States) in 1965. [65] During the World Wars, Hispanic Americans and immigrants helped stabilize the American economy from falling due to the industrial boom in the Midwest in states such as Michigan, Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Iowa, Wisconsin, and Minnesota. While a percentage of Americans fled their jobs for the war, Hispanics took their jobs in the industrial world. This can explain why there is such a high concentration of Hispanic Americans in metro areas such as the Chicago-Elgin-Naperville, Detroit-Warren-Dearborn, and Cleveland-Elyria areas. [64]

Hispanic and Latino Americans were actively involved in the broader civil rights movement of the 20th century, advocating for equal rights, social justice, and an end to discrimination and segregation. Organizations such as the [League of United Latin American Citizens](/League_of_United_Latin_American_Citizens) (LULAC) and the [United Farm Workers](/United_Farm_Workers) (UFW) fought for the rights of Hispanic and Latino workers and communities.

Hispanic contributions in the historical past and present of the United States are addressed in more detail below (See Notables and their contributions). To recognize the current and historic contributions of Hispanic Americans, on September 17, 1968, President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) designated a week in mid-September as National Hispanic Heritage Week, with [Congress](/United_States_Congress)'s authorization. In 1988, President [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) extended the observance to a month, designated [National Hispanic Heritage Month](/National_Hispanic_Heritage_Month). [66][67] Hispanic Americans became the largest minority group in 2004. [68]

Civil rights activist [Cesar Chavez](/Cesar_Chavez), flanked by [Brown Berets](/Brown_Berets), at a 1971 rally during the [Chicano movement](/Chicano_movement)

Hispanic and Latino Americans increasingly sought political representation and empowerment during the 20th century. The election of individuals such as [Edward Roybal](/Edward_Roybal), [Henry B. González](/Henry_B._Gonz%C3%A1lez), and [Dennis Chávez](/Dennis_Ch%C3%A1vez) to Congress marked significant milestones in Hispanic political representation. Additionally, the appointment of individuals like [Lauro Cavazos](/Lauro_Cavazos) and [Bill Richardson](/Bill_Richardson) to cabinet positions highlighted the growing influence of Hispanic and Latino leaders in government.

Hispanic and Latino Americans became the largest minority group in the United States, contributing significantly to the country's population growth. Efforts to preserve and promote Hispanic and Latino culture and heritage continued in the 21st century, including initiatives to support bilingual education, celebrate cultural traditions and festivals, and recognize the contributions of Hispanic and Latino individuals and communities to American society.

## Demographics

•
Main article: [Demographics of Hispanic and Latino Americans](/Demographics_of_Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans)

•
See also: [Demographics of the United States](/Demographics_of_the_United_States) and [List of U.S. states by Hispanic and Latino population](/List_of_U.S._states_by_Hispanic_and_Latino_population)

Hispanic Americans population pyramid in 2020

As of 2020, Hispanics accounted for 19–20% of the US population, or 62–65 million people. [69] The US Census Bureau later estimated that Hispanics were under-counted by 5.0%, or 3.3 million persons, in the US census, which explains the 3 million range in the number above. In contrast, Whites were over-counted by about 3 million. [70] The Hispanic growth rate over the April 1, 2000, to July 1, 2007, period was 28.7%—about four times the rate of the nation's total population growth (at 7.2%). [71] The growth rate from July 1, 2005, to July 1, 2006, alone was 3.4% [72] —about three and a half times the rate of the nation's total population growth (at 1.0%). [71] Based on the 2010 census, Hispanics are now the largest minority group in 191 out of 366 metropolitan areas in the United States. [73] The projected Hispanic population of the United States for July 1, 2050, is 132.8 million people, or 30.2% of the nation's total projected population on that date. [74]

