Of the nation's total Hispanic population, 49% (21.5 million) live in [California](/California) or [Texas](/Texas). [77] In 2022, [New York City](/New_York_City) and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) began receiving significant numbers of Latino migrants from the state of Texas, mostly originating from [Venezuela](/Venezuela), [Ecuador](/Ecuador), [Colombia](/Colombia), and [Honduras](/Honduras). [78]

Over half of the Hispanic population is concentrated in the [Southwest](/Southwestern_United_States) region, mostly composed of Mexican Americans. [California](/California) and [Texas](/Texas) have some of the largest populations of Mexicans and Central American Hispanics in the United States. The [Northeast](/Northeastern_United_States) region is dominated by [Dominican Americans](/Dominican_Americans) and [Puerto Ricans](/Stateside_Puerto_Ricans), having the highest concentrations of both in the country. In the Mid-Atlantic region, centered on the [DC Metro Area](/Washington_metropolitan_area), [Salvadoran Americans](/Salvadoran_Americans) are the largest of Hispanic groups. [Florida](/Florida) is dominated by [Cuban Americans](/Cuban_Americans) and Puerto Ricans. In both the [Great Lakes states](/Great_Lakes_region) and the [South Atlantic states](/South_Atlantic_states), Mexicans and Puerto Ricans dominate. Mexicans dominate in the rest of the country, including the [West](/Western_United_States), [South Central](/South_Central_United_States), and [Great Plains](/Great_Plains) states.

