The Spanish dialects spoken in the United States differ depending on the country of origin of the person or the person's family heritage. However, generally, Spanish spoken in the [Southwest](/Southwestern_United_States) is [Mexican Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish) or [Chicano Spanish](/Chicano). A variety of Spanish native to the Southwest spoken by descendants of the early Spanish colonists in [New Mexico](/New_Mexico) and [Colorado](/Colorado) is known as Traditional [New Mexican Spanish](/New_Mexican_Spanish). One of the major distinctions of Traditional New Mexican Spanish is its use of distinct vocabulary and grammatical forms that make [New Mexican Spanish](/New_Mexican_Spanish) unique among Spanish dialects. The Spanish spoken in the [East Coast](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States) is generally [Caribbean Spanish](/Caribbean_Spanish) and is heavily influenced by the Spanish of [Cuba](/Cuban_Spanish), the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Spanish), and [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rican_Spanish). [Isleño Spanish](/Isle%C3%B1o_Spanish), descended from [Canarian Spanish](/Canarian_Spanish), is the historic Spanish dialect spoken by the descendants of the earliest Spanish colonists beginning in the 18th century in [Louisiana](/Louisiana). Spanish spoken elsewhere throughout the country varies, although it is generally [Mexican Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish). [96][168]

Heritage Spanish speakers tend to speak Spanish with near-native level phonology but a more limited command of morphosyntax. [169] Hispanics who speak Spanish as a second language often speak with English accents.

#### Spanglish and English dialects

•
Main articles: [Chicano English](/Chicano_English), [Spanglish](/Spanglish), [Miami § Dialect](/Miami), and [New York Latino English](/New_York_Latino_English)

•
See also: [List of English words of Spanish origin](/List_of_English_words_of_Spanish_origin)

[El Museo del Barrio](/El_Museo_del_Barrio), in Manhattan, is the oldest museum in the country dedicated to Latino art.

Hispanics have influenced the way Americans speak with the introduction of many Spanish words into the English language. Among younger generations of Hispanics, [Spanglish](/Spanglish), a term for any mix of Spanish and English, is common in speaking. As they are fluent in both languages, speakers will often switch between Spanish and English throughout the conversation. Spanglish is particularly common in Hispanic-majority cities and communities such as [Miami](/Miami), [Hialeah](/Hialeah,_Florida), [San Antonio](/San_Antonio), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), and parts of [New York City](/New_York_City). [170]

Hispanics have also influenced the way English is spoken in the United States. In Miami, for example, the [Miami dialect](/Miami) has evolved as the most common form of English spoken and heard in Miami today. This is a native dialect of English, and was developed among second- and third-generation [Cuban Americans](/Cuban_American) in Miami. Today, it is commonly heard everywhere throughout the city. [Gloria Estefan](/Gloria_Estefan) and [Enrique Iglesias](/Enrique_Iglesias) are examples of people who speak with the Miami dialect. Another major English dialect is spoken by [Chicanos](/Chicano) and [Tejanos](/Tejano) in the [Southwestern United States](/Southwestern_United_States), called [Chicano English](/Chicano_English). [George Lopez](/George_Lopez) and [Selena](/Selena) are examples of speakers of Chicano English. [171] An English dialect spoken by Puerto Ricans and other Hispanic groups is called [New York Latino English](/New_York_Latino_English); [Jennifer Lopez](/Jennifer_Lopez) and [Cardi B](/Cardi_B) are examples of people who speak with the New York Latino dialect.

When speaking in English, American Hispanics may often insert Spanish tag and filler items such as *tú sabes*, *este*, and *órale*, into sentences as a marker of ethnic identity and solidarity. The same often occurs with grammatical words like *pero*. [172]

### Religion

The [Cathedral of San Carlos Borromeo](/Cathedral_of_San_Carlos_Borromeo_(Monterey,_California)), built in 1791 in [Monterey, California](/Monterey,_California), is the oldest serving cathedral in the country.
[San Antonio Missions National Park](/San_Antonio_Missions_National_Historical_Park) in Texas, a [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site), comprising four historic mission sites.

According to a [Pew Center](/Pew_Center) study conducted in 2019, the majority of Hispanic Americans are [Christians](/Christianity) (72%). [173] Among American Hispanics, as of 2018–19, 47% are [Catholic](/Roman_Catholic_Church), 24% are [Protestant](/Protestant), 1% are [Mormon](/Mormon), less than 1% are [Orthodox Christian](/Orthodoxy), 3% are members of non-Christian faiths, and 23% are [unaffiliated](/Irreligion_in_the_United_States). [173] The proportion of Hispanics who are Catholic has dropped from 2009 (when it was 57%), while the proportion of unaffiliated Hispanics has increased since 2009 (when it was 15%). [173] Among the Hispanic Protestant community, most are [evangelical], but some belong to [mainline denominations](/Mainline_Protestant). [174] Compared to Catholic, unaffiliated, and mainline Protestant Hispanics, Evangelical Protestant Hispanics are substantially more likely to attend services weekly, pray daily, and adhere to [biblical liberalism](/Liberal_Christianity). [174] As of 2014, about 67% of Hispanic Protestants and about 52% of Hispanic Catholics were renewalist, meaning that they described themselves as [Pentecostal](/Pentecostalism) or [charismatic Christians](/Charismatic_Christianity) (in the Catholic tradition, called [Catholic charismatic renewal](/Catholic_charismatic_renewal)). [175]

Catholic affiliation is much higher among first-generation Hispanic immigrants than it is among second- and third-generation Hispanic immigrants, who exhibit a fairly high rate of conversion to Protestantism or the unaffiliated camp. [176] According to [Andrew Greeley](/Andrew_Greeley), as many as 600,000 American Hispanics leave Catholicism for Protestant churches every year, and this figure is much higher in [Texas](/Texas) and [Florida](/Florida). [177] Hispanic Catholics are developing youth and social programs to retain members. [178]

Founded in 1609, the [National Shrine of Our Lady of La Leche](/National_Shrine_of_Our_Lady_of_La_Leche), in [St. Augustine, Florida](/St._Augustine,_Florida), is the oldest shrine in the country.

Hispanics make up a substantial proportion (almost 40%) of [Catholics in the United States](/Catholic_Church_in_the_United_States), [179] although the number of American Hispanic [priests](/Catholic_priests) is low relative to Hispanic membership in the church. [180] In 2019, [José Horacio Gómez](/Jos%C3%A9_Horacio_G%C3%B3mez), [Archbishop of Los Angeles](/Archbishop_of_Los_Angeles) and a naturalized American citizen born in Mexico, was elected as president of the [US Conference of Catholic Bishops](/United_States_Conference_of_Catholic_Bishops). [179]

